          "body": "Chapter 8 raised the meat-sacrificed-to-idols question and answered it with the principle of love that limits knowledge. Chapter 9 modeled apostolic self-limitation — Paul's foregone rights as the embodiment of the ethic. Chapter 10 now grounds the whole argument theologically: sacramental eating is participation, and the Christian's participation in Christ is exclusive. The chapter resolves the tension between chapter 8 (which seemed to permit attendance if the weak weren't watching) and chapter 10 (which absolutely prohibits attendance because of what such eating IS). The two are not contradictory — chapter 8 addresses incidental eating of idol-meat in non-cultic contexts (which is fine if no brother stumbles); chapter 10 addresses sacramental eating in actual pagan worship (which is never fine). The whole argument lands on three principles: flee idolatry (14), seek the neighbor's good (24), do all to God's glory (31)."
